The Boston housing data contains characteristics of 506 houses in the Boston
 suburbs and their selling price.
 The dataset is loaded by the 
\family typewriter
ExamData.R
\family default
 file.
 The original data is in 
\family typewriter
Boston
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
?Boston
\family default
 will present the help file with information on all variables.
 We are here interested in modeling the response variable 
\family typewriter
medv
\family default
 (value of the house in 1000$) as a function of all the other variables
 in the dataset.
 The 
\family typewriter
ExamData.R
\family default
 also prepares the data so that the vector 
\family typewriter
y
\family default
 contains the response variable and the matrix 
\family typewriter
X
\family default
 contains the covariates (with the first column being ones to model the
 intercept term).
 The vector 
\family typewriter
\color black
covNames
\family default
\color inherit
 contains the names of all the covariates.
 Use the conjugate prior
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta\vert\sigma^{2} & \sim N(0,10^{2}\sigma^{2}I)\\
\sigma^{2} & \sim Inv-\chi^{2}(1,5^{2}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

